    std::function<void()> func;
public:
    MyClass(std::function<void()> f) : func(std::move(f)) {}

    void call() {
        func();
    }
};
```

In this example, `std::move(f)` is used to efficiently transfer ownership of the callable object to the member variable `func`.

### Conclusion

In summary, whether to pass `std::function` by value or by const-reference depends on the intended use of the function. In general, for simple invocations where no ownership transfer is needed, passing by const-reference is preferred for efficiency. However, if the function intends to store the callable for later use, passing by value ensures that the function takes ownership of the callable object safely. Understanding these distinctions is crucial for writing high-performance, maintainable C++ code.

