       // Reset to default color (usually gray on black)
       setConsoleColor(7, 0);
   }
   ```

5. **Using the Function**  
   Call `printColoredText` with different color combinations:

   ```cpp
   int main() {
       printColoredText("Hello, World!", 10, 0); // Green text on black background
       printColoredText("Warning!", 12, 0);       // Red text on black background
       printColoredText("Success!", 10, 0);       // Green text on black background
       printColoredText("Info:", 14, 0);           // Yellow text on black background
       return 0;
   }
   ```

### Example Output

When you run this small program in the Windows console, you'll see "Hello, World!" in green, "Warning!" in red, "Success!" in green again, and "Info:" in yellow. This visually distinct output can help in conveying different statuses or messages effectively.

### Conclusion

By utilizing the Windows console API, you can easily add color to your console output using C++. This method allows for a richer user interface and can be particularly useful in applications that require status messages or alerts. Remember that the color settings might differ based on user preferences or command line settings, so always test your application in the intended environment to ensure the visibility and aesthetics are as expected.

